id: 1f9b0a13-6d12-4a3e-97c4-3e7b2a11b6c9
name: Soft Cell (2019)
description: >
  The Soft Cell campaign is a long-term cyber espionage operation targeting telecom providers globally.
  The adversary exploited public-facing applications (PHP) to gain access,
  installed web shells for persistence, performed credential dumping and lateral movement,
  and exfiltrated Call Detail Records (CDRs) and other sensitive data from telecom infrastructure.
atomic_ordering:
  # INITIAL ACCESS
  - T1190       # Exploit Public-Facing Application
  # EXECUTION
  - T1059       # Command and Scripting Interpreter
  - T1203       # Exploitation for Client Execution
  # PERSISTENCE
  - T1505       # Server Components (web shells / IIS modules)
  - T1136       # Create Account
  # PRIVILEGE ESCALATION
  - T1068       # Exploitation for Privilege Escalation
  # DEFENSE EVASION
  - T1027       # Obfuscated Files or Information
  - T1070       # Indicator Removal on Host
  # CREDENTIAL ACCESS
  - T1003       # OS Credential Dumping
  # DISCOVERY
  - T1083       # File and Directory Discovery
  - T1018       # Remote System Discovery
  - T1087       # Account Discovery
  # LATERAL MOVEMENT
  - T1021       # Remote Services (RDP, SMB)
  - T1077       # Windows Admin Shares
  # COLLECTION
  - T1005       # Data from Local System
  - T1114       # Email Collection
  # EXFILTRATION
  - T1020       # Automated Exfiltration
  - T1041       # Exfiltration over C2 Channel
  # IMPACT (optional)
  - T1499       # Endpoint DoS
  - T1561       # Disk Wipe
phases:
  - phase: Initial Access
    description: >
      Exploit public-facing applications (IIS, WebLogic, ColdFusion) to deploy web shells and gain foothold.
  - phase: Execution
    description: >
      Execute commands and scripts through dropped web shells or command interpreters.
  - phase: Persistence
    description: >
      Install malicious IIS modules or create new accounts to maintain long-term access.
  - phase: Privilege Escalation
    description: >
      Use local exploits to elevate privileges and gain domain-level control.
  - phase: Defense Evasion
    description: >
      Hide activity through obfuscation and remove traces from event logs.
  - phase: Credential Access
    description: >
      Extract credentials from LSASS and SAM databases.
  - phase: Discovery
    description: >
      Enumerate network, accounts, and databases containing subscriber data.
  - phase: Lateral Movement
    description: >
      Move between systems via RDP, SMB, or administrative shares.
  - phase: Collection
    description: >
      Gather Call Detail Records (CDRs), logs, and internal emails.
  - phase: Exfiltration
    description: >
      Automatically exfiltrate collected data through established C2 channels.
  - phase: Impact
    description: >
      Cause service disruptions or data destruction during final cleanup stages.
goals:
  - Access to telecom core systems and databases containing subscriber and call metadata.
  - Maintain persistent access for long-term espionage.
  - Exfiltrate large volumes of CDR and network data stealthily.




